  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If a truck is hauling 1000 pounds of parakeets that are all sitting on their perch does it get 1000 pounds lighter if they all fly at the same time?",
  "response": "No, the truck does not get 1000 pounds lighter if the parakeets all start flying at the same time. Even though the parakeets may not be in contact with their perch, they are still inside the truck and their weight is still exerted on the truck as they fly.\n\nWhen the parakeets fly, they push air downward to stay aloft, and this action results in an equal and opposite reaction: the air exerts an upward force on the parakeets. The downward force exerted by the air (created by the flapping wings of the parakeets) will be transferred to the truck's floor and surfaces. In essence, the forces involved still result in the truck bearing the same total weight as if the parakeets were perched.\n\nTherefore, regardless of whether the parakeets are sitting or flying inside the truck, the overall weight impacting the truck remains the same, and the truck does not get lighter.",
